<p>I'm a huge D&amp;D nerd. I've also always been fascinated by table-top roleplaying games with excessively complicated rules &#8212; and the idea of building a game you could play with by yourself. After <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/vezaz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1403034); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1403034&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609721446" alt="Vezaz" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1403034)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/vezaz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1403034); return false;">Vezaz</a></span> mentioned his excellent <a href="/1914">1914</a>, I realized I wanted to replicate that sense of growing confusion and horror &#8212; but using something like <em>Rolemaster</em>.</p>
<p>One of the common complaints about this one is that it runs right up against the line of not even being anomalous (more than a few people have asked me what about it is spooky or supernatural). While I think that's a wholly valid complaint, I also think that, for me, this was an exercise in pure atmosphere and restraint &#8212; I wanted to see if I could make something 100% believable and still spooky.</p>
<p>YMMV!</p>
</div>
